<section class="lineage-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="lineage-header reveal d1">
      <p class="lineage-pillar-label">Pillar I — Virtue</p>
      <h2 class="lineage-pillar-name">Tell the truth. Even when it costs you.</h2>
      <p class="lineage-pillar-tagline">What they wrote about honesty and moral courage in the age of machines.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d2">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Alan Turing</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1912–1954 · Father of Computer Science & Artificial Intelligence</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>We can only see a short distance ahead, but we can see plenty there that needs to be done.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Alan Turing, "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," Mind, 1950</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet I — <strong>Tell the Truth. Even When It Costs You.</strong> Turing told the truth about what machines could become when the entire scientific establishment said it was fantasy. He told the truth about who he was when his country made that truth a criminal offense. A Grithosian does not wait for the world to be ready for the truth. You say what needs to be said, do what needs to be done, and let the consequences come.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Sometimes it is the people no one can imagine anything of who do the things no one can imagine.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Alan Turing, as portrayed in The Imitation Game (2014), adapted from Andrew Hodges' Alan Turing: The Enigma</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet III — <strong>Own Your Wins. But Do Right in the Dark.</strong> Turing cracked Enigma in total secrecy. No glory. No headlines. Millions of lives saved by a man the world wasn't allowed to thank. He did right in the darkest possible conditions — classified, invisible, alone. A Grithosian does the work that matters whether anyone notices or not.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Tim Berners-Lee</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1955–Present · Inventor of the World Wide Web</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>This is for everyone.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Tim Berners-Lee, tweet during the 2012 London Olympics Opening Ceremony</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet III — <strong>Own Your Wins. But Do Right in the Dark.</strong> Berners-Lee built the most valuable technology in human history and gave it away. No patent. No IPO. No billion-dollar payday. He owned the win — then handed it to humanity. A Grithosian understands that some victories are too important to monetize. Do right because it's right. The scoreboard is irrelevant.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The Web as I envisaged it, we have not seen it yet. The future is still so much bigger than the past.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Tim Berners-Lee, interview with the BBC, 2009</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet II — <strong>Keep Your Word Like Your Life Depends on It.</strong> Berners-Lee made a promise to the world: the Web would stay open. Decades later, while tech giants tried to wall it off, he kept that promise. He founded the World Wide Web Consortium and fought for open standards when selling out would have made him the richest man alive. A Grithosian keeps their word even when breaking it would be profitable.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Linus Torvalds</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1969–Present · Creator of Linux & Git</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Talk is cheap. Show me the code.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Linus Torvalds, Linux Kernel Mailing List</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet I — <strong>Tell the Truth. Even When It Costs You.</strong> Torvalds has zero patience for posturing. You can talk about what you're going to build, or you can build it. In the open-source world, the code is the truth — it either works or it doesn't. A Grithosian doesn't hide behind words. The work speaks. Show me what you built. Show me what you shipped. Everything else is noise.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>I'm doing a (free) operating system (just a hobby, won't be big and professional like gnu).</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Linus Torvalds, Usenet post to comp.os.minix, August 25, 1991</div>
      <div class="bridge">
