    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Fei-Fei Li</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1976–Present · Creator of ImageNet — Architect of the Modern AI Revolution</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>If we want machines to think, we need to teach them to see.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Fei-Fei Li, TED Talk, "How we teach computers to understand pictures," 2015</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XI — <strong>Leave Something Behind.</strong> Li didn't build an AI product. She built the foundation — ImageNet, 14 million labeled images — that made everyone else's AI breakthroughs possible. Every image recognition system, every self-driving car, every AI that can "see" traces back to her dataset. She left behind infrastructure, not a product. A Grithosian builds the foundation that others build on. That's the legacy that compounds across generations.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>We didn't set out to solve AI. We set out to understand the visual world.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Fei-Fei Li, on the origins of ImageNet, Stanford Human-Centered AI Institute</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Burn Bright, Not Long.</strong> Li immigrated from China as a teenager, worked in a dry cleaner to survive, and burned through every obstacle between her and the science that mattered. She didn't chase the AI hype. She pursued understanding — and that pursuit ignited a revolution. A Grithosian burns for the question, not the answer. The brightness of the pursuit is what changes the world.
